posts.raw_content:
Bill Gates Carbon Capture

Bill Gates, through his climate solutions fund Breakthrough Energy, is actively investing in multiple carbon capture startups, with the most recent developments centered on a $40 million grant to Canadian company Deep Sky Corp. for its Deep Sky Alpha Direct Air Capture (DAC) test facility in Alberta, which is expected to begin operations in Spring 2025 This project aims to test and optimize multiple DAC technologies before commercial deployment, with CO2 to be stored 2 km underground Concurrently, another Bill Gates-backed startup, Graphyte, has been scaling its carbon casting technology, using waste biomass to create stable, plant-based bricks that store carbon underground for over 1,000 years, with its Arkansas facility already operational and capturing over 15,000 tonnes of CO2 annually

Deep Sky Corp. Direct Air Capture Project

Breakthrough Energy Catalyst has committed a $40 million grant to Deep Sky Corp. to build the Deep Sky Alpha test facility in Innisfail, Alberta
The facility, which is under construction, is expected to be operational by Spring 2025 and will use renewable energy to power its operations
It will serve as a test bed for up to eight different Direct Air Capture technologies, aiming to optimize them for commercial-scale deployment
The captured CO2 will be permanently stored 2 km underground in a deep saline aquifer
Graphyte Carbon Casting Technology

Graphyte, backed by Breakthrough Energy Ventures, has developed a process called "carbon casting" that turns waste biomass from logging and farming into stable bricks
These bricks are dried and sealed to prevent decomposition, allowing the carbon to be stored underground for at least 1,000 years
The company's facility in Pine Bluff, Arkansas, began operations in early 2024 and is designed to capture over 15,000 tonnes of CO2 annually, with plans to scale to 50,000 tonnes in 2025
Graphyte claims its process is highly efficient, requiring only a tenth of the energy of traditional Direct Air Capture and achieving a carbon efficiency of 90% initially, rising to 98% with renewable power
The company can offer carbon removal for less than $100 per ton, meeting the Biden administration's "earthshot" goal
